# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: singular-perturbation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] In physics and fluid mechanics, a **boundary layer** is the thin layer of fluid in the immediate vicinity of a bounding surface formed by the fluid flowing along the surface.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The fluid's interaction with the wall induces a no-slip boundary condition (zero velocity at the wall).
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The flow velocity then monotonically increases above the surface until it returns to the bulk flow velocity.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The thin layer consisting of fluid whose velocity has not yet returned to the bulk flow velocity is called the velocity boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The air next to a human is heated, resulting in gravity-induced convective airflow, which results in both a velocity and thermal boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] A breeze disrupts the boundary layer, and hair and clothing protect it, making the human feel cooler or warmer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] On an aircraft wing, the velocity boundary layer is the part of the flow close to the wing, where viscous forces distort the surrounding non-viscous flow.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] In the Earth's atmosphere, the atmospheric boundary layer is the air layer (~ 1 km) near the ground.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] It is affected by the surface; day-night heat flows caused by the sun heating the ground, moisture, or momentum transfer to or from the surface.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Laminar boundary layers can be loosely classified according to their structure and the circumstances under which they are created.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] When a fluid rotates and viscous forces are balanced by the Coriolis effect (rather than convective inertia), an Ekman layer forms.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] In the theory of heat transfer, a thermal boundary layer occurs.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] A surface can have multiple types of boundary layer simultaneously.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The viscous nature of airflow reduces the local velocities on a surface and is responsible for skin friction.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The layer of air over the wing's surface that is slowed down or stopped by viscosity, is the boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] There are two different types of boundary layer flow: laminar and turbulent.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The laminar boundary is a very smooth flow, while the turbulent boundary layer contains swirls or "eddies." The laminar flow creates less skin friction drag than the turbulent flow, but is less stable.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Boundary layer flow over a wing surface begins as a smooth laminar flow.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] As the flow continues back from the leading edge, the laminar boundary layer increases in thickness.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] At some distance back from the leading edge, the smooth laminar flow breaks down and transitions to a turbulent flow.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] From a drag standpoint, it is advisable to have the transition from laminar to turbulent flow as far aft on the wing as possible, or have a large amount of the wing surface within the laminar portion of the boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The low energy laminar flow, however, tends to break down more suddenly than the turbulent layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The aerodynamic boundary layer was first hypothesized by Ludwig Prandtl in a paper presented on August 12, 1904, at the third International Congress of Mathematicians in Heidelberg, Germany.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This allows a closed-form solution for the flow in both areas by making significant simplifications of the full Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The same hypothesis is applicable to other fluids (besides air) with moderate to low viscosity such as water.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] For the case where there is a temperature difference between the surface and the bulk fluid, it is found that the majority of the heat transfer to and from a body takes place in the vicinity of the velocity boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This again allows the equations to be simplified in the flow field outside the boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The pressure distribution throughout the boundary layer in the direction normal to the surface (such as an airfoil) remains relatively constant throughout the boundary layer, and is the same as on the surface itself.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The thickness of the velocity boundary layer is normally defined as the distance from the solid body to the point at which the viscous flow velocity is 99% of the freestream velocity (the surface velocity of an inviscid flow).
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Displacement thickness is an alternative definition stating that the boundary layer represents a deficit in mass flow compared to inviscid flow with slip at the wall.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] It is the distance by which the wall would have to be displaced in the inviscid case to give the same total mass flow as the viscous case.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The no-slip condition requires the flow velocity at the surface of a solid object be zero and the fluid temperature be equal to the temperature of the surface.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The flow velocity will then increase rapidly within the boundary layer, governed by the boundary layer equations, below.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The thermal boundary layer thickness is similarly the distance from the body at which the temperature is 99% of the freestream temperature.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The ratio of the two thicknesses is governed by the Prandtl number.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] If the Prandtl number is 1, the two boundary layers are the same thickness.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] If the Prandtl number is greater than 1, the thermal boundary layer is thinner than the velocity boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] If the Prandtl number is less than 1, which is the case for air at standard conditions, the thermal boundary layer is thicker than the velocity boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] In high-performance designs, such as gliders and commercial aircraft, much attention is paid to controlling the behavior of the boundary layer to minimize drag.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] First, the boundary layer adds to the effective thickness of the body, through the displacement thickness, hence increasing the pressure drag.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Secondly, the shear forces at the surface of the wing create skin friction drag.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] At high Reynolds numbers, typical of full-sized aircraft, it is desirable to have a laminar boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This results in a lower skin friction due to the characteristic velocity profile of laminar flow.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] However, the boundary layer inevitably thickens and becomes less stable as the flow develops along the body, and eventually becomes turbulent, the process known as boundary layer transition.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] One way of dealing with this problem is to suck the boundary layer away through a porous surface (see Boundary layer suction).
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This can reduce drag, but is usually impractical due to its mechanical complexity and the power required to move the air and dispose of it.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Natural laminar flow (NLF) techniques push the boundary layer transition aft by reshaping the airfoil or fuselage so that its thickest point is more aft and less thick.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This reduces the velocities in the leading part and the same Reynolds number is achieved with a greater length.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] At lower Reynolds numbers, such as those seen with model aircraft, it is relatively easy to maintain laminar flow.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This gives low skin friction, which is desirable.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] However, the same velocity profile which gives the laminar boundary layer its low skin friction also causes it to be badly affected by adverse pressure gradients.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] As the pressure begins to recover over the rear part of the wing chord, a laminar boundary layer will tend to separate from the surface.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Such flow separation causes a large increase in the pressure drag, since it greatly increases the effective size of the wing section.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] In these cases, it can be advantageous to deliberately trip the boundary layer into turbulence at a point prior to the location of laminar separation, using a turbulator.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The fuller velocity profile of the turbulent boundary layer allows it to sustain the adverse pressure gradient without separating.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Thus, although the skin friction is increased, overall drag is decreased.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This is the principle behind the dimpling on golf balls, as well as vortex generators on aircraft.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Special wing sections have also been designed which tailor the pressure recovery so laminar separation is reduced or even eliminated.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This represents an optimum compromise between the pressure drag from flow separation and skin friction from induced turbulence.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] When using half-models in wind tunnels, a peniche is sometimes used to reduce or eliminate the effect of the boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The deduction of the **boundary layer equations** was one of the most important advances in fluid dynamics.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Using an order of magnitude analysis, the well-known governing Navier–Stokes equations of viscous fluid flow can be greatly simplified within the boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Notably, the characteristic of the partial differential equations (PDE) becomes parabolic, rather than the elliptical form of the full Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This greatly simplifies the solution of the equations.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] By making the boundary layer approximation, the flow is divided into an inviscid portion (which is easy to solve by a number of methods) and the boundary layer, which is governed by an easier to solve PDE.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] where u and $\upsilon$ are the velocity components, $\rho$ is the density, p is the pressure, and $\nu$ is the kinematic viscosity of the fluid at a point.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The approximation states that, for a sufficiently high Reynolds number the flow over a surface can be divided into an outer region of inviscid flow unaffected by viscosity (the majority of the flow), and a region close to the surface where viscosity is important (the boundary layer).
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Let u and $\upsilon$ be streamwise and transverse (wall normal) velocities respectively inside the boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The order of magnitude analysis assumes the streamwise length scale significantly larger than the transverse length scale inside the boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] It follows that variations in properties in the streamwise direction are generally much lower than those in the wall normal direction.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Apply this to the continuity equation shows that $\upsilon$ , the wall normal velocity, is small compared with u the streamwise velocity.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Since the static pressure p is independent of y , then pressure at the edge of the boundary layer is the pressure throughout the boundary layer at a given streamwise position.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The external pressure may be obtained through an application of Bernoulli's equation.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Let U be the fluid velocity outside the boundary layer, where u and U are both parallel.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] These approximations are used in a variety of practical flow problems of scientific and engineering interest.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The above analysis is for any instantaneous laminar or turbulent boundary layer, but is used mainly in laminar flow studies since the mean flow is also the instantaneous flow because there are no velocity fluctuations present.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This simplified equation is a parabolic PDE and can be solved using a similarity solution often referred to as the Blasius boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Since the solution is not unique from mathematical perspective, to the solution can be added any one of an infinite set of eigenfunctions as shown by Stewartson and Paul A.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Von Kármán derived the integral equation by integrating the boundary layer equation across the boundary layer in 1921.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The energy integral was derived by Wieghardt.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] For steady two-dimensional boundary layers, von Mises introduced a transformation which takes x and $\psi$ (stream function) as independent variables instead of x and y and uses a dependent variable $\chi =U^{2}-u^{2}$ instead of u .
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This transformation is later extended to compressible boundary layer by von Kármán and HS Tsien.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] For steady two-dimensional compressible boundary layer, Luigi Crocco introduced a transformation which takes x and u as independent variables instead of x and y and uses a dependent variable $\tau =\mu \partial u/\partial y$ (shear stress) instead of u .
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The treatment of turbulent boundary layers is far more difficult due to the time-dependent variation of the flow properties.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] One of the most widely used techniques in which turbulent flows are tackled is to apply Reynolds decomposition.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Here the instantaneous flow properties are decomposed into a mean and fluctuating component with the assumption that the mean of the fluctuating component is always zero.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Using a similar order-of-magnitude analysis, the above equations can be reduced to leading order terms.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This equation does not satisfy the no-slip condition at the wall.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Like Prandtl did for his boundary layer equations, a new, smaller length scale must be used to allow the viscous term to become leading order in the momentum equation.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] In the limit of infinite Reynolds number, the pressure gradient term can be shown to have no effect on the inner region of the turbulent boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The new "inner length scale" $\eta$ is a viscous length scale, and is of order ${\frac {\nu }{u_{*}}}$ , with $u_{*}$ being the velocity scale of the turbulent fluctuations, in this case a friction velocity.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Unlike the laminar boundary layer equations, the presence of two regimes governed by different sets of flow scales (i.e. the inner and outer scaling) has made finding a universal similarity solution for the turbulent boundary layer difficult and controversial.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] To find a similarity solution that spans both regions of the flow, it is necessary to asymptotically match the solutions from both regions of the flow.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Such analysis will yield either the so-called log-law or power-law.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Similar approaches to the above analysis has also been applied for thermal boundary layers, using the energy equation in compressible flows.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The additional term ${\overline {u'v'}}$ in the turbulent boundary layer equations is known as the Reynolds shear stress and is unknown a priori.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The solution of the turbulent boundary layer equations therefore necessitates the use of a turbulence model, which aims to express the Reynolds shear stress in terms of known flow variables or derivatives.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The lack of accuracy and generality of such models is a major obstacle in the successful prediction of turbulent flow properties in modern fluid dynamics.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] A constant stress layer exists in the near wall region.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Due to the damping of the vertical velocity fluctuations near the wall, the Reynolds stress term will become negligible and we find that a linear velocity profile exists.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This is only true for the very near wall region.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] In 1928, the French engineer André Lévêque observed that convective heat transfer in a flowing fluid is affected only by the velocity values very close to the surface.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] For flows of large Prandtl number, the temperature/mass transition from surface to freestream temperature takes place across a very thin region close to the surface.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Therefore, the most important fluid velocities are those inside this very thin region in which the change in velocity can be considered linear with normal distance from the surface.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] where *θ* is the tangent of the Poiseuille parabola intersecting the wall.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Although Lévêque's solution was specific to heat transfer into a Poiseuille flow, his insight helped lead other scientists to an exact solution of the thermal boundary-layer problem.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Schuh observed that in a boundary-layer, *u* is again a linear function of *y*, but that in this case, the wall tangent is a function of *x*.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This results in a very good approximation, even for low $Pr$ numbers, so that only liquid metals with $Pr$ much less than 1 cannot be treated this way.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] In 1962, Kestin and Persen published a paper describing solutions for heat transfer when the thermal boundary layer is contained entirely within the momentum layer and for various wall temperature distributions.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] For the problem of a flat plate with a temperature jump at $x=x_{0}$ , they propose a substitution that reduces the parabolic thermal boundary-layer equation to an ordinary differential equation.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The solution to this equation, the temperature at any point in the fluid, can be expressed as an incomplete gamma function.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Schlichting proposed an equivalent substitution that reduces the thermal boundary-layer equation to an ordinary differential equation whose solution is the same incomplete gamma function.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Analytic solutions can be derived with the time-dependent self-similar Ansatz for the incompressible boundary layer equations including heat conduction.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] As is well known from several textbooks, heat transfer tends to decrease with the increase in the boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Recently, it was observed on a practical and large scale that wind flowing through a photovoltaic generator tends to "trap" heat in the PV panels under a turbulent regime due to the decrease in heat transfer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Paul Richard Heinrich Blasius derived an exact solution to the above laminar boundary layer equations.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The thickness of the boundary layer $\delta$ is a function of the Reynolds number for laminar flow.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Note that in many cases, the no-slip boundary condition holds that $v_{S}$ , the fluid velocity at the surface of the plate equals the velocity of the plate at all locations.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] If the plate is not moving, then $v_{S}=0$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] A much more complicated derivation is required if fluid slip is allowed.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] In fact, the Blasius solution for laminar velocity profile in the boundary layer above a semi-infinite plate can be easily extended to describe Thermal and Concentration boundary layers for heat and mass transfer respectively.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] For the momentum balance, kinematic viscosity $\nu$ can be considered to be the *momentum diffusivity*.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] In the energy balance this is replaced by thermal diffusivity $\alpha ={k/\rho C_{P}}$ , and by mass diffusivity $D_{AB}$ in the mass balance.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] In thermal diffusivity of a substance, k is its thermal conductivity, $\rho$ is its density and $C_{P}$ is its heat capacity.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Subscript AB denotes diffusivity of species A diffusing into species B.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Under the assumption that $\alpha =D_{AB}=\nu$ , these equations become equivalent to the momentum balance.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Thus, for Prandtl number $Pr=\nu /\alpha =1$ and Schmidt number $Sc=\nu /D_{AB}=1$ the Blasius solution applies directly.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Accordingly, this derivation uses a related form of the boundary conditions, replacing v with T or $c_{A}$ (absolute temperature or concentration of species A).
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The subscript S denotes a surface condition.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Using the streamline function Blasius obtained the following solution for the shear stress at the surface of the plate.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] where $\delta _{T},\delta _{c}$ are the regions of flow where T and $c_{A}$ are less than 99% of their far field values.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Because the Prandtl number of a particular fluid is not often unity, German engineer E.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Polhausen who worked with Ludwig Prandtl attempted to empirically extend these equations to apply for $Pr\neq 1$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] His results can be applied to $Sc$ as well.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] From this solution, it is possible to characterize the convective heat/mass transfer constants based on the region of boundary layer flow.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Fourier's law of conduction and Newton's Law of Cooling are combined with the flux term derived above and the boundary layer thickness.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This gives the local convective constant $h_{x}$ at one point on the semi-infinite plane.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] These solutions apply for laminar flow with a Prandtl/Schmidt number greater than 0.6.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Many of the principles that apply to aircraft also apply to ships, submarines, and offshore platforms, with water as the primary fluid of concern rather than air.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] As water is not an ideal fluid, ships moving in water experience resistance.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] While the front of the ship faces normal pressure forces due to the fluid surrounding it, the aft portion sees a lower acting component of pressure due to the boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This leads to higher resistance due to pressure known as 'viscous pressure drag' or 'form drag'.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] For ships, unlike aircraft, one deals with incompressible flows, where change in water density is negligible (a pressure rise close to 1000kPa leads to a change of only 2–3 kg/m3).
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This field of fluid dynamics is called hydrodynamics.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] A ship engineer designs for hydrodynamics first, and for strength only later.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] The boundary layer development, breakdown, and separation become critical because the high viscosity of water produces high shear stresses.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] This effect was exploited in the Tesla turbine, patented by Nikola Tesla in 1913.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] It is referred to as a bladeless turbine because it uses the boundary layer effect and not a fluid impinging upon the blades as in a conventional turbine.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Boundary layer turbines are also known as cohesion-type turbine, bladeless turbine, and Prandtl layer turbine (after Ludwig Prandtl).
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] By using the transient and viscous force equations for a cylindrical flow you can predict the transient boundary layer thickness by finding the Womersley Number ( $N_{w}$ ).
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] where $N_{w}$ = Womersley Number; $\rho$ = density; v = velocity; $w=$ frequency of oscillations; $\delta _{1}$ = length of transient boundary layer; $\mu$ = viscosity; L = characteristic length.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] By using the convective and viscous force equations at the boundary layer for a cylindrical flow you can predict the convective flow conditions at the boundary layer by finding the dimensionless Reynolds Number ( $Re$ ).
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] where $Re$ = Reynolds Number; $\rho$ = density; v = velocity; $\delta _{2}$ = length of convective boundary layer; $\mu$ = viscosity; L = characteristic length.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Boundary layer ingestion promises an increase in aircraft fuel efficiency with an aft-mounted propulsor ingesting the slow fuselage boundary layer and re-energising the wake to reduce drag and improve propulsive efficiency.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] To operate in distorted airflow, the fan is heavier and its efficiency is reduced, and its integration is challenging.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] It is used in concepts like the Aurora D8 or the French research agency Onera's Nova, saving 5% in cruise by ingesting 40% of the fuselage boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Airbus presented the Nautilius concept at the ICAS congress in September 2018: to ingest all the fuselage boundary layer, while minimizing the azimuthal flow distortion, the fuselage splits into two spindles with 13-18:1 bypass ratio fans.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] Propulsive efficiencies are up to 90% like counter-rotating open rotors with smaller, lighter, less complex and noisy engines.
[src:singular-perturbation/boundary-layer] It could lower fuel burn by over 10% compared to a usual underwing 15:1 bypass ratio engine.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] In mathematics, the **method of matched asymptotic expansions** is a common approach to finding an accurate approximation to the solution to an equation, or system of equations.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] It is particularly used when solving singularly perturbed differential equations.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] In the Russian literature, these methods were known under the name of "intermediate asymptotics" and were introduced in the work of Yakov Zeldovich and Grigory Barenblatt.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] In a large class of singularly perturbed problems, the domain may be divided into two or more subdomains.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] In one of these, often the largest, the solution is accurately approximated by an asymptotic series found by treating the problem as a regular perturbation (i.e., by setting a relatively small parameter to zero).
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The other subdomains consist of one or more small regions in which that approximation is inaccurate, generally because the perturbation terms in the problem are not negligible there.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] These areas are referred to as *transition layers* in general, and specifically as *boundary layers* or *interior layers* depending on whether they occur at the domain boundary (as is the usual case in applications) or inside the domain, respectively.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] An approximation in the form of an asymptotic series is obtained in the transition layer(s) by treating that part of the domain as a separate perturbation problem.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] This approximation is called the *inner solution*, and the other is the *outer solution*, named for their relationship to the transition layer(s).
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The outer and inner solutions are then combined through a process called "matching" in such a way that an approximate solution for the whole domain is obtained.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] Consider the boundary value problem $\varepsilon y''+(1+\varepsilon )y'+y=0,$ where y is a function of independent time variable t , which ranges from 0 to 1, the boundary conditions are $y(0)=0$ and $y(1)=1$ , and $\varepsilon$ is a small parameter, such that $0<\varepsilon \ll 1$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] Alternatively, consider that when y and t are both of size *O*(1), the four terms on the left hand side of the original equation are respectively of sizes $O(\varepsilon )$ , *O*(1), $O(\varepsilon )$ and *O*(1).
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] This has solution $y=Ae^{-t}$ for some constant A .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] Applying the boundary condition $y(0)=0$ , we would have $A=0$ ; applying the boundary condition $y(1)=1$ , we would have $A=e$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] It is therefore impossible to satisfy both boundary conditions, so $\varepsilon =0$ is not a valid approximation to make across the whole of the domain (i.e. this is a singular perturbation problem).
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] From this we infer that there must be a boundary layer at one of the endpoints of the domain where $\varepsilon$ needs to be included.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] This region will be where $\varepsilon$ is no longer negligible compared to the independent variable t , i.e. t and $\varepsilon$ are of comparable size, i.e. the boundary layer is adjacent to $t=0$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] Therefore, the other boundary condition $y(1)=1$ applies in this outer region, so $A=e$ , i.e. $y_{\mathrm {O} }=e^{1-t}$ is an accurate approximate solution to the original boundary value problem in this outer region.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] In the inner region, t and $\varepsilon$ are both tiny, but of comparable size, so define the new *O*(1) time variable $\tau =t/\varepsilon$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] This has solution $y=B-Ce^{-\tau }$ for some constants B and C .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] We use matching to find the value of the constant B .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The idea of matching is that the inner and outer solutions should agree for values of t in an intermediate (or overlap) region, i.e. where $\varepsilon \ll t\ll 1$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] We need the outer limit of the inner solution to match the inner limit of the outer solution, i.e., $\lim _{\tau \to \infty }y_{\mathrm {I} }=\lim _{t\to 0}y_{\mathrm {O} },$ which gives $B=e$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The above problem is the simplest of the simple problems dealing with matched asymptotic expansions.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] Notice, the intuitive idea for matching of taking the limits i.e. ${\textstyle \lim _{\tau \to \infty }y_{\mathrm {I} }=\lim _{t\to 0}y_{\mathrm {O} },}$ does not apply at this level.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] This is simply because the underlined term does not converge to a limit.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The methods to follow in these types of cases are either to go for a) method of an intermediate variable or using b) the Van-Dyke matching rule.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The former method is cumbersome and works always whereas the Van-Dyke matching rule is easy to implement but with limited applicability.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] A concrete boundary value problem having all the essential ingredients is the following.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The conventional outer expansion $y_{\mathrm {O} }=y_{0}+\varepsilon y_{1}+\cdots$ gives $y_{0}=\alpha e^{1/x}-1$ , where $\alpha$ must be obtained from matching.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The problem has boundary layers both on the left and on the right.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The left boundary layer near 0 has a thickness $\varepsilon ^{1/2}$ whereas the right boundary layer near 1 has thickness $\varepsilon$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The ${\mathcal {O}}(1)$ inhomogeneous condition on the left provides us the reason to start the expansion at ${\mathcal {O}}(1)$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] This with $1-1$ van-Dyke matching gives $\alpha =0$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The ${\mathcal {O}}(1)$ inhomogeneous condition on the right provides us the reason to start the expansion at ${\mathcal {O}}(1)$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] This with $1-1$ van-Dyke matching gives $B=2$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] To obtain our final, matched, composite solution, valid on the whole domain, one popular method is the uniform method.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] In this method, we add the inner and outer approximations and subtract their overlapping value, $\,y_{\mathrm {overlap} }$ , which would otherwise be counted twice.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The overlapping value is the outer limit of the inner boundary layer solution, and the inner limit of the outer solution; these limits were above found to equal e .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] Note that this expression correctly reduces to the expressions for $y_{\mathrm {I} }$ and $y_{\mathrm {O} }$ when t is $O(\varepsilon )$ and *O*(1), respectively.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] This final solution satisfies the problem's original differential equation (shown by substituting it and its derivatives into the original equation).
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] Also, the boundary conditions produced by this final solution match the values given in the problem, up to a constant multiple.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] This implies, due to the uniqueness of the solution, that the matched asymptotic solution is identical to the exact solution up to a constant multiple.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] This is not necessarily always the case, any remaining terms should go to zero uniformly as $\varepsilon \rightarrow 0$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] Not only does our solution successfully approximately solve the problem at hand, it closely approximates the problem's exact solution.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] It happens that this particular problem is easily found to have exact solution $y(t)={\frac {e^{-t}-e^{-t/\varepsilon }}{e^{-1}-e^{-1/\varepsilon }}},$ which has the same form as the approximate solution, by the multiplying constant.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The approximate solution is the first term in a binomial expansion of the exact solution in powers of $e^{1-1/\varepsilon }$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] Conveniently, we can see that the boundary layer, where $y'$ and $y''$ are large, is near $t=0$ , as we supposed earlier.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] If we had supposed it to be at the other endpoint and proceeded by making the rescaling $\tau =(1-t)/\varepsilon$ , we would have found it impossible to satisfy the resulting matching condition.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] For many problems, this kind of trial and error is the only way to determine the true location of the boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The problem above is a simple example because it is a single equation with only one dependent variable, and there is one boundary layer in the solution.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] Harder problems may contain several co-dependent variables in a system of several equations, and/or with several boundary and/or interior layers in the solution.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] It is often desirable to find more terms in the asymptotic expansions of both the outer and the inner solutions.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The appropriate form of these expansions is not always clear: while a power-series expansion in $\varepsilon$ may work, sometimes the appropriate form involves fractional powers of $\varepsilon$ , functions such as $\varepsilon \log \varepsilon$ , et cetera.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] As in the above example, we will obtain outer and inner expansions with some coefficients which must be determined by matching.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] Methods of matched asymptotic expansions have been developed to find approximate solutions to the Smoluchowski convection–diffusion equation, which is a singularly perturbed second-order differential equation.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] The problem has been studied particularly in the context of colloid particles in linear flow fields, where the variable is given by the pair distribution function around a test particle.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] In the limit of low Péclet number, the convection–diffusion equation also presents a singularity at infinite distance (where normally the far-field boundary condition should be placed) due to the flow field being linear in the interparticle separation.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] This problem can be circumvented with a spatial Fourier transform as shown by Jan Dhont.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] This leads to an approximate theory for the encounter rate of two interacting colloid particles in a linear flow field in good agreement with the full numerical solution.
[src:singular-perturbation/method-of-matched-asymptotic-expansions] When the Péclet number is significantly larger than one, the singularity at infinite separation no longer occurs and the method of matched asymptotics can be applied to construct the full solution for the pair distribution function across the entire domain.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] In electronics, a **relaxation oscillator** is a nonlinear electronic oscillator circuit that produces a nonsinusoidal repetitive output signal, such as a triangle wave or square wave.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] The period of the oscillator depends on the time constant of the capacitor or inductor circuit.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] The active device switches abruptly between charging and discharging modes, and thus produces a discontinuously changing repetitive waveform.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] This contrasts with the other type of electronic oscillator, the harmonic or linear oscillator, which uses an amplifier with feedback to excite resonant oscillations in a resonator, producing a sine wave.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] The term *relaxation oscillator*, though often used in electronics engineering, is also applied to dynamical systems in many diverse areas of science that produce nonlinear oscillations and can be analyzed using the same mathematical model as electronic relaxation oscillators.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Relaxation oscillations are characterized by two alternating processes on different time scales: a long relaxation period during which the system approaches an equilibrium point, alternating with a short impulsive period in which the equilibrium point shifts.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] The period of a relaxation oscillator is mainly determined by the relaxation time constant.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Relaxation oscillations are a type of limit cycle and are studied in nonlinear control theory.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] The first relaxation oscillator circuit, the astable multivibrator, was invented by Henri Abraham and Eugene Bloch using vacuum tubes during World War I.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Balthasar van der Pol first distinguished relaxation oscillations from harmonic oscillations, originated the term "relaxation oscillator", and derived the first mathematical model of a relaxation oscillator, the influential Van der Pol oscillator model, in 1920.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Van der Pol borrowed the term *relaxation* from mechanics; the discharge of the capacitor is analogous to the process of *stress relaxation*, the gradual disappearance of deformation and return to equilibrium in an inelastic medium.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Before the advent of microelectronics, simple relaxation oscillators often used a negative resistance device with hysteresis such as a thyratron tube, neon lamp, or unijunction transistor, however today they are more often built with dedicated integrated circuits such as the 555 timer chip.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Relaxation oscillators are generally used to produce low-frequency signals for such applications as blinking lights and electronic beepers.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] They are also used in voltage-controlled oscillators (VCOs), inverters and switching power supplies, dual-slope analog to digital converters, and in function generators to produce square and triangle waves.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Relaxation oscillators are widely used because they are easier to design than linear oscillators, are easier to fabricate on integrated circuit chips because they do not require inductors like LC oscillators, and can be tuned over a wide frequency range.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] However they have more phase noise and poorer frequency stability than linear oscillators.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] The capacitor is charged by the input source causing the voltage across the capacitor to rise.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] The threshold device does not conduct at all until the capacitor voltage reaches its threshold (trigger) voltage.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] It then increases heavily its conductance in an avalanche-like manner because of the inherent positive feedback, which quickly discharges the capacitor.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] When the voltage across the capacitor drops to some lower threshold voltage, the device stops conducting and the capacitor begins charging again, and the cycle repeats ad infinitum.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] If the threshold element is a neon lamp, the circuit also provides a flash of light with each discharge of the capacitor.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] This lamp example is depicted below in the typical circuit used to describe the Pearson–Anson effect.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] The discharging duration can be extended by connecting an additional resistor in series to the threshold element.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] The two resistors form a voltage divider; so, the additional resistor has to have low enough resistance to reach the low threshold.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] A similar relaxation oscillator can be built with a 555 timer IC (acting in astable mode) that takes the place of the neon bulb above.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] That is, when a chosen capacitor is charged to a design value, (e.g., 2/3 of the power supply voltage) comparators within the 555 timer flip a transistor switch that gradually discharges that capacitor through a chosen resistor (which determine the RC time constant) to ground.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] At the instant the capacitor falls to a sufficiently low value (e.g., 1/3 of the power supply voltage), the switch flips to let the capacitor charge up again.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] The popular 555's comparator design permits accurate operation with any supply from 5 to 15 volts or even wider.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Other, non-comparator oscillators may have unwanted timing changes if the supply voltage changes.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Alternatively, when the capacitor reaches each threshold, the charging source can be switched from the positive power supply to the negative power supply or vice versa.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] The earlier inverting Schmitt trigger animated example operates on the same principle (since the Schmitt trigger internally performs comparison).
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] This section will analyze a similar implementation using a comparator as a discrete component.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] This relaxation oscillator is a hysteretic oscillator, named this way because of the hysteresis created by the positive feedback loop implemented with the comparator (similar to an operational amplifier).
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] A circuit that implements this form of hysteretic switching is known as a Schmitt trigger.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Alone, the trigger is a bistable multivibrator.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] However, the slow negative feedback added to the trigger by the RC circuit causes the circuit to oscillate automatically.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] That is, the addition of the RC circuit turns the hysteretic bistable multivibrator into an astable multivibrator.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] The system is in unstable equilibrium if both of the inputs and the output of the comparator are at zero volts.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] In other words, because the output of the comparator is now positive, the non-inverting input to the comparator is also positive, and continues to increase as the output increases, due to the voltage divider.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] After a short time, the output of the comparator is the positive voltage rail, $V_{DD}$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] The inverting input and the output of the comparator are linked by a series RC circuit.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Because of this, the inverting input of the comparator asymptotically approaches the comparator output voltage with a time constant RC.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] At the point where voltage at the inverting input is greater than the non-inverting input, the output of the comparator falls quickly due to positive feedback.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] This is because the non-inverting input is less than the inverting input, and as the output continues to decrease, the difference between the inputs gets more and more negative.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Again, the inverting input approaches the comparator's output voltage asymptotically, and the cycle repeats itself once the non-inverting input is greater than the inverting input, hence the system oscillates.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Notice there are two solutions to the differential equation, the driven or particular solution and the homogeneous solution.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Solving for the driven solution, observe that for this particular form, the solution is a constant.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] $V_{-}$ is the sum of the particular and homogeneous solution.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Solving for B requires evaluation of the initial conditions.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] First let's assume that $V_{dd}=-V_{ss}$ for ease of calculation.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Ignoring the initial charge up of the capacitor, which is irrelevant for calculations of the frequency, note that charges and discharges oscillate between ${\frac {V_{dd}}{2}}$ and ${\frac {V_{ss}}{2}}$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] For the circuit above, Vss must be less than 0.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Half of the period (T) is the same as time that $V_{\text{out}}$ switches from Vdd.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] When Vss is not the inverse of Vdd we need to worry about asymmetric charge up and discharge times.
[src:singular-perturbation/relaxation-oscillator] Which reduces to the above result in the case that $V_{dd}=-V_{ss}$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] In mathematics, a **singular perturbation** problem is a problem containing a small parameter that cannot be approximated by setting the parameter value to zero.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Here $\varepsilon$ is the small parameter of the problem and $\delta _{n}(\varepsilon )$ are a sequence of functions of $\varepsilon$ of increasing order, such as $\delta _{n}(\varepsilon )=\varepsilon ^{n}$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] This is in contrast to regular perturbation problems, for which a uniform approximation of this form can be obtained.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Singularly perturbed problems are generally characterized by dynamics operating on multiple scales.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Several classes of singular perturbations are outlined below.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] The term "singular perturbation" was coined in the 1940s by Kurt Otto Friedrichs and Wolfgang R.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] A perturbed problem whose solution can be approximated on the whole problem domain, whether space or time, by a single asymptotic expansion has a regular perturbation.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Most often in applications, an acceptable approximation to a regularly perturbed problem is found by simply replacing the small parameter $\varepsilon$ by zero everywhere in the problem statement.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] This corresponds to taking only the first term of the expansion, yielding an approximation that converges, perhaps slowly, to the true solution as $\varepsilon$ decreases.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] The solution to a singularly perturbed problem cannot be approximated in this way: As seen in the examples below, a singular perturbation generally occurs when a problem's small parameter multiplies its highest operator.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Thus naively taking the parameter to be zero changes the very nature of the problem.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] In the case of differential equations, boundary conditions cannot be satisfied; in algebraic equations, the possible number of solutions is decreased.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Singular perturbation theory is a rich and ongoing area of exploration for mathematicians, physicists, and other researchers.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] The methods used to tackle problems in this field are many.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] The more basic of these include the method of matched asymptotic expansions and WKB approximation for spatial problems, and in time, the Poincaré–Lindstedt method, the method of multiple scales and periodic averaging.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] The numerical methods for solving singular perturbation problems are also very popular.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] For books on singular perturbation in ODE and PDE's, see for example Holmes, *Introduction to Perturbation Methods*, Hinch, *Perturbation methods* or Bender and Orszag, *Advanced Mathematical Methods for Scientists and Engineers*.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Each of the examples described below shows how a naive perturbation analysis, which assumes that the problem is regular instead of singular, will fail.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Some show how the problem may be solved by more sophisticated singular methods.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Differential equations that contain a small parameter that premultiplies the highest order term typically exhibit boundary layers, so that the solution evolves in two different scales.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Its solution when $\varepsilon =0.1$ is the solid curve shown below.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Note that the solution changes rapidly near the origin.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] If we naively set $\varepsilon =0$ , we would get the solution labelled "outer" below which does not model the boundary layer, for which *x* is close to zero.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] For more details that show how to obtain the uniformly valid approximation, see method of matched asymptotic expansions.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] An electrically driven robot manipulator can have slower mechanical dynamics and faster electrical dynamics, thus exhibiting two time scales.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] In such cases, we can divide the system into two subsystems, one corresponding to faster dynamics and other corresponding to slower dynamics, and then design controllers for each one of them separately.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Through a singular perturbation technique, we can make these two subsystems independent of each other, thereby simplifying the control problem.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] The second equation indicates that the dynamics of $x_{2}$ is much faster than that of $x_{1}$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] on some interval of time and that, as $\varepsilon$ decreases toward zero, the system will approach the solution more closely in that same interval.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] In fluid mechanics, the properties of a slightly viscous fluid are dramatically different outside and inside a narrow boundary layer.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Thus the fluid exhibits multiple spatial scales.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Reaction–diffusion systems in which one reagent diffuses much more slowly than another can form spatial patterns marked by areas where a reagent exists, and areas where it does not, with sharp transitions between them.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] where u is the prey and v is the predator, have been shown to exhibit such patterns.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] Consider the problem of finding all roots of the polynomial $p(x)=\varepsilon x^{3}-x^{2}+1$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] In the limit $\varepsilon \to 0$ , this cubic degenerates into the quadratic $1-x^{2}$ with roots at $x=\pm 1$ .
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] To find the other root, singular perturbation analysis must be used.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] We must then deal with the fact that the equation degenerates into a quadratic when we let $\varepsilon$ tend to zero, in that limit one of the roots escapes to infinity.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] To prevent this root from becoming invisible to the perturbative analysis, we must rescale x to keep track with this escaping root so that in terms of the rescaled variables, it does not escape.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] We define a rescaled variable $y=x\varepsilon ^{\nu }$ where the exponent $\nu$ will be chosen such that we rescale just fast enough so that the root is at a finite value of y in the limit of $\varepsilon$ to zero, but such that it does not collapse to zero where the other two roots will end up.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] We can see that for $\nu <1$ the $y^{3}$ is dominated by the lower degree terms, while at $\nu =1$ it becomes as dominant as the $y^{2}$ term while they both dominate the remaining term.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] This point where the highest order term will no longer vanish in the limit $\varepsilon$ to zero by becoming equally dominant to another term, is called significant degeneration; this yields the correct rescaling to make the remaining root visible.
[src:singular-perturbation/singular-perturbation] We are then interested in the root at $y_{0}=1$ ; the double root at $y_{0}=0$ are the two roots that we've found above that collapse to zero in the limit of an infinite rescaling.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] In physics, **slowly varying envelope approximation** (**SVEA**, sometimes also called **slowly varying asymmetric approximation** or **SVAA**) is the assumption that the envelope of a forward-travelling wave pulse varies slowly in time and space compared to a period or wavelength.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] This requires the spectrum of the signal to be narrow-banded—hence it is also referred to as the **narrow-band approximation**.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] The slowly varying envelope approximation is often used because the resulting equations are in many cases easier to solve than the original equations, reducing the order of—all or some of—the highest-order partial derivatives.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] But the validity of the assumptions which are made need to be justified.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] In the *slowly varying envelope approximation* (SVEA) it is assumed that the complex amplitude *E*0(**r**, *t*) only varies slowly with **r** and t.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] This inherently implies that *E*(**r**, *t*) represents waves propagating forward, predominantly in the **k**0 direction.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] This is a hyperbolic partial differential equation, like the original wave equation, but now of first-order instead of second-order.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] It is valid for coherent forward-propagating waves in directions near the **k**0-direction.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] The space and time scales over which *E*0 varies are generally much longer than the spatial wavelength and temporal period of the carrier wave.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] A numerical solution of the envelope equation thus can use much larger space and time steps, resulting in significantly less computational effort.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] Assume wave propagation is dominantly in the z-direction, and **k**0 is taken in this direction.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] The SVEA is only applied to the second-order spatial derivatives in the z-direction and time.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] This is a parabolic partial differential equation.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] This equation has enhanced validity as compared to the full SVEA: It represents waves propagating in directions significantly different from the z-direction.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] where $\ell _{\mathsf {g}}$ is the length over which the radiation pulse is amplified, $\ell _{\mathsf {p}}$ is the pulse width and v is the group velocity of the radiating system.
[src:singular-perturbation/slowly-varying-envelope-approximation] These conditions are much less restrictive in the relativistic limit where ${\frac {v}{c}}$ is close to 1, as in a free-electron laser, compared to the usual conditions required for the SVEA validity.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] In the study of dynamical systems, the **van der Pol oscillator** (named for Dutch physicist Balthasar van der Pol) is a non-conservative, oscillating system with non-linear damping.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] It evolves in time according to the second-order differential equation ${d^{2}x \over dt^{2}}=\mu (1-x^{2}){dx \over dt}-x,$ where x is the position coordinate—which is a function of the time t—and μ is a scalar parameter indicating the nonlinearity and the strength of the damping.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] The Van der Pol oscillator was originally proposed by the Dutch electrical engineer and physicist Balthasar van der Pol while he was working at Philips.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] Van der Pol found stable oscillations, which he subsequently called relaxation-oscillations and are now known as a type of limit cycle, in electrical circuits employing vacuum tubes.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] When these circuits are driven near the limit cycle, they become entrained, i.e. the driving signal pulls the current along with it.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] Van der Pol and his colleague, van der Mark, reported in the September 1927 issue of *Nature* that at certain drive frequencies an irregular noise was heard, which was later found to be the result of deterministic chaos.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] The Van der Pol equation has a long history of being used in both the physical and biological sciences.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] For instance, in biology, Fitzhugh and Nagumo extended the equation in a planar field as a model for action potentials of neurons.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] The equation has also been utilised in seismology to model the two plates in a geological fault, and in studies of phonation to model the right and left vocal fold oscillators.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] Liénard's theorem can be used to prove that the system has a limit cycle.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] As μ moves from less than zero to more than zero, the spiral sink at origin becomes a spiral source, and a limit cycle appears "out of the blue" with radius two.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] This is because the transition is not generic: when *ε* = 0, both the differential equation becomes linear, and the origin becomes a circular node.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] Note that the dynamics of the original Van der Pol oscillator is not affected due to the one-way coupling between the time-evolutions of *x* and *y* variables.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] This may, in principle, lead to quantization of the Van der Pol oscillator.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] Such a Hamiltonian also connects the geometric phase of the limit cycle system having time dependent parameters with the Hannay angle of the corresponding Hamiltonian system.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] The quantum van der Pol oscillator, which is the quantum mechanical version of the classical van der Pol oscillator, has been proposed using a Lindblad equation to study its quantum dynamics and quantum synchronization.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] Note the above Hamiltonian approach with an auxiliary second-order equation produces unbounded phase-space trajectories and hence cannot be used to quantize the van der Pol oscillator.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] *μ→*0) the van der Pol oscillator reduces to the Stuart–Landau equation.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] The Stuart–Landau equation in fact describes an entire class of limit-cycle oscillators in the weakly-nonlinear limit.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] The form of the classical Stuart–Landau equation is much simpler, and perhaps not surprisingly, can be quantized by a Lindblad equation which is also simpler than the Lindblad equation for the van der Pol oscillator.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] The quantum Stuart–Landau model has played an important role in the study of quantum synchronisation (where it has often been called a van der Pol oscillator although it cannot be uniquely associated with the van der Pol oscillator).
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] The relationship between the classical Stuart–Landau model (*μ→*0) and more general limit-cycle oscillators (arbitrary *μ*) has also been demonstrated numerically in the corresponding quantum models.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] where A is the amplitude, or displacement, of the wave function and ω is its angular velocity.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] Author James Gleick described a vacuum tube Van der Pol oscillator in his book from 1987 *Chaos: Making a New Science*.
[src:singular-perturbation/van-der-pol-oscillator] According to a *New York Times* article, Gleick received a modern electronic Van der Pol oscillator from a reader in 1988.
